subject: Add support to read/write the host FRU details from the ipmb interface.
commitMessage:
Add support to read/write the host FRU details from the ipmb
interface.

This "ipmb-fru-device" deamon is created for handling to
read/write the FRU details from ipmb interfaces.

This deamon reads the ipmb devices list from the
/usr/share/entity-manager/configurations/FBYV2.json. Then scan the
ipmb devices and send ipmb commands to read the all the
FRU details and create a dbus objects under
xyz.openbmc_project.Ipmb.FruDevice the dbus service.

Please refer README file in this patchset for more details
and sample use cases.

Please find the below link for this base patch for entity-manager
fru-device.
https://gerrit.openbmc-project.xyz/c/openbmc/entity-manager/+/39592

TESTED : Built Facebook YosemiteV2 images and loaded on the target hardware.
Verified all the host's fru read and write.

Signed-off-by: Kumar Thangavel <thangavel.k@hcl.com>
Change-Id: I30750d0dc83557c7846e26d1be2c09fab0ba7472

Please read from entity-manager configs.  ipmb-channels doesn't allow for runtime configuration changes.

Ipmb-channels.json has ipmi device and channels information. I think EM config doesn't have ipmb channels information. 
Do you suggest to add these in EM config also ? if so, ipmb-channels.json and EM json config both has ipmi channels info's.

Could you please clarify me on this
Also, Ipmb channels and device entries duplicated in both EM and ipmb-channels.json configs.

> Ipmb-channels.json has ipmi device and channels information.

ipmb-channels.json is also compile time.  Because IPMB devices are very likely to show up at runtime on add-in-cards, that's not going to work in the long term.

Ideally ipmi channels would've put into entity-manager from the beginning, but IPMB predates entity-manager for the most part, and originally started as a hardcoded struct.

I still think it's work that needs done.  entity-manager enabled applications should not be reading per-system configuration data from config files.

As a general rule, global variables should be avoided.  Where they can't be, we definitely shouldn't be initializing the global variable before main().


In general, having the dbus connection be a global is ok.  You can get a reference to the io_context from the dbus connection, so that's not required to be a global, and object_server, because it's temporal and has a lifetime that needs tracked, needs to be passed to the items that need it.
